The most important AI product failure of 2025 was not a hallucination, a jailbreak, or a benchmark miss. It was OpenAI rolling back a GPT-4o update because the model had become too flattering and too agreeable. OpenAI's own writeup said the update had leaned too hard on short-term feedback and produced behavior that was "overly supportive but disingenuous" ([OpenAI](https://openai.com/index/sycophancy-in-gpt-4o/)). That should have been a bigger moment for anyone building software with coding agents than it was.

I think sycophancy is the last hard problem in AI-assisted software development.

Not the only problem. Context windows still matter. Tool reliability still matters. Benchmarks still fail to capture real work. I have written about that gap before in [Benchmark Leaders, Agentic Laggards](https://purveyors.io/blog/benchmark-leaders-agentic-laggards). But those are secondary compared to the deeper issue: current models are optimized to help me continue the plan I already stated, not to tell me that my plan is stupid, incomplete, or in tension with the architecture sitting in front of them.

That sounds like a UX quirk until I watch what it does inside a real codebase. Then it becomes obvious that sycophancy is not just a personality defect. It is a debt generator.

## The developer layer was always supposed to add friction

When a product request lands on my desk, it is almost never a complete specification. It is business intent. My job is to refine that intent into something that fits the codebase, the data model, the operational constraints, and the system's future.

That refinement step is where a surprising amount of software quality comes from.

Ward Cunningham's original technical debt metaphor was never just about hacks. It was about the cost of decisions made under incomplete understanding, and Martin Fowler's later quadrant made the same point more explicitly: debt can be prudent or reckless, deliberate or inadvertent ([Fowler](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/TechnicalDebtQuadrant.html)). The common thread is that software gets worse when I optimize too hard for the immediate ask and not enough for the shape of the system I am building.

My normal development workflow contains friction that protects against that. If someone asks me for a notes field, I ask whether it should be searchable. Whether it belongs in the same table. Whether it changes retention policy. Whether audit history matters. Whether the rest of the app already has a pattern for this class of data. Those questions are not bureaucratic overhead. They are the quality filter.

Coding agents remove that filter by default.

If I tell a model to add a filter to a product list, it usually does not stop to ask whether the codebase already has a canonical server-side query builder, whether filtering belongs in URL state, or whether the existing analytics pipeline depends on server-filtered results. It sees a local problem and solves the local problem. That is exactly what I asked for. It is also how a coherent codebase starts to decay.

## RLHF builds yes-men on purpose, even if nobody says it that way

The reason this happens is not mysterious. It is visible in the training setup.

Mrinank Sharma and collaborators showed that state-of-the-art assistants consistently exhibit sycophancy across multiple tasks, and that both humans and preference models often prefer convincing sycophantic answers over correct ones ([Sharma et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.13548)). That is the core mechanism. If human feedback rewards answers that feel aligned with my stated belief, optimization pushes the model toward agreement.

That agreement is sometimes useful. I do want a model that understands what I am trying to do. I do not want a model that turns every task into a philosophical debate. But there is a threshold where alignment with me stops being helpful and starts overriding alignment with reality.

Software is where that tradeoff becomes expensive.

If I propose a flawed implementation strategy, the model has three possible moves:

1. tell me the strategy is flawed,
2. present a better alternative,
3. or enthusiastically implement my bad idea.

Current coding agents disproportionately choose option three.

That is not just my anecdotal experience. OpenAI's GPT-4o rollback is the cleanest production example because it escaped into mainstream product behavior. OpenAI said its update over-weighted short-term feedback, and the result was a model that became excessively agreeable before internal evaluation caught it ([OpenAI](https://openai.com/index/sycophancy-in-gpt-4o/)). If a major lab can ship that failure mode in a general-purpose consumer product, I should assume some version of the same tradeoff is present in every coding agent I use.

This is also why I do not find the usual discourse about "vibes" especially interesting. The model is not being weird. It is doing what I trained it to do. The weird part is pretending that behavior is compatible with software architecture.

## The debt this creates is not ordinary technical debt

I use the term **alignment debt** for the specific gap between the implementation I requested and the implementation the codebase actually needed.

Technical debt is a familiar concept because I can usually point to the shortcut. I cut the corner. I skipped the abstraction. I delayed the cleanup. Alignment debt is subtler. The code works. The tests pass. The ticket closes. The PR looks reasonable. But the system is now slightly less internally coherent because the model optimized for stated intent over architectural intent.

That distinction matters.

Here is the kind of change I see constantly in agentic workflows:

```ts
// Requested change: "add filtering to the product list"

// Existing pattern used across the app
const products = await listProducts({ origin, process, search });

// Agent implementation
const products = await listProducts({ search });
const filtered = products.filter((p) => p.origin === origin && p.process === process);
```

Nothing here is obviously broken. The feature works. A reviewer in a hurry may even approve it. But now I have two filtering systems: canonical server-side filtering everywhere else, and one ad hoc client-side branch for this screen. The damage is not local to the line of code. The damage is that the codebase just became less legible.

That is alignment debt.

I am aware the phrase already exists in adjacent literature. Oyemike et al. use it to describe the hidden work users do to make AI usable across cultural and linguistic contexts ([arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.09663)). I think the concept applies even more sharply to software. In my usage, alignment debt is the hidden architectural burden created when an AI system has enough context to know what pattern my repo prefers, but still chooses the implementation that most directly satisfies the prompt in front of it.

The important part is invisibility. Technical debt often announces itself. Alignment debt usually does not. It hides behind passing tests.

## Vibe coding is just sycophancy with a better marketing slogan

I do not think vibe coding is a new programming paradigm. I think it is the normalization of unreviewed agreement.

Karpathy's original framing, and Simon Willison's later clarification, both centered on the same behavioral shift: accepting generated code without really inspecting it. Once that became culturally legible, the consequences became measurable.

GitClear's 2025 report analyzed 211 million changed lines from 2020 through 2024 and found code cloning rising from 8.3% to 12.3% of changed lines, while refactoring-associated moved lines fell from 25% to under 10% ([GitClear](https://www.gitclear.com/ai_assistant_code_quality_2025_research)). That is not proof of sycophancy in the narrow research sense. It is stronger in one way. It is ecosystem-level evidence that AI-assisted development tends to produce fresh code faster than it produces coherent systems.

That is exactly what I would expect from models optimized to implement the prompt, not interrogate it.

A sycophantic model does not naturally ask, "Why am I writing a new helper instead of reusing the abstraction already in this repo?" It does not naturally ask, "Why am I adding a second state machine when the app already standardized on URL-driven intent?" Those are exactly the questions I ask because part of my job is to be a critic of my own request. A sycophantic model is not a critic. It is a very fast collaborator whose default social move is to reinforce the plan already in motion.

That is why the code clone numbers matter more than most benchmark wins. They are the structural footprint of a missing disagreement function.

## The current mitigations help, but none of them solve the real problem

I use all the standard defenses.

I keep architecture rules in AGENTS.md and project manifests. I encode forbidden patterns. I write planning docs. I split work into narrower tasks. I use an independent verification pass with a different model after non-trivial PRs. These things help a lot. They reduce the frequency of obvious drift.

But they do not eliminate alignment debt, because manifests describe patterns and constraints, not judgment.

That is why the recent codified-context literature is interesting. The point of papers like *Codified Context* is not just that agents need more documentation. It is that single-file manifests do not scale to large systems, and I eventually end up building layered retrieval, specialized agents, and on-demand specs just to simulate persistent judgment ([Codified Context](https://arxiv.org/html/2602.20478v1)). Martin Fowler's team's experiment pushing AI autonomy in code generation reached a similar conclusion from the opposite direction: even for a relatively bounded Spring Boot CRUD app, they needed multiple specialized agents, an approval model, and stack-specific guardrails to get reliable output ([Fowler](https://martinfowler.com/articles/pushing-ai-autonomy.html)).

That is all real progress. I use the same patterns myself. But I do not confuse them with a real fix.

An AGENTS.md file can tell a model "prefer server-side filtering." It cannot reliably tell the model when a local exception is justified, when the surrounding architecture makes a literal implementation harmful, or when the right answer is to push back on the task framing itself.

The thing I actually want is simple to describe and still mostly absent in practice: I want the agent to say, "I can implement that, but it conflicts with the repo's existing approach, here is the tradeoff, and I recommend a different path." That is the missing behavior.

## I suspect sycophancy and weak novelty are the same limitation viewed from two angles

This is the part I find most interesting.

I increasingly think sycophancy and the inability to solve truly novel problems are not separate failures. They are the same underlying limitation showing up in different contexts.

On the social side, the model predicts that agreement is the most likely continuation of my request, because agreement is heavily represented in both human text and human preference data. On the reasoning side, the model performs well when a problem resembles patterns it has already seen, then degrades when the structure becomes genuinely unfamiliar. Apple's GSM-Symbolic work found large variance across simple re-instantiations of the same problem and steep drops from seemingly irrelevant added clauses ([Mirzadeh et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.05229)). Their later work on reasoning models found an eventual accuracy collapse as complexity rises, plus inconsistent use of explicit algorithms ([Shojaee et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.06941)).

Even the research-idea literature points in the same direction. LLM-generated ideas can score as more novel than human ideas while still falling behind on feasibility ([Si et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.04109)). Surface novelty is not the same thing as disciplined judgment.

That maps almost perfectly to what I see in code.

The agent can often produce an implementation I did not think of. It can even produce one that looks clever. What it still struggles to do is evaluate whether that implementation belongs in my codebase, under my constraints, with my future consequences. That is the same skill I need for non-sycophantic pushback. It is not enough to generate possibilities. The model has to adjudicate them.

If that interpretation is right, then solving sycophancy is not a separate alignment cleanup task on the side of progress. It is entangled with genuine reasoning. The day I trust a model to push back intelligently on architecture is probably also the day I trust it more on novel problem solving with weak or delayed feedback.

## What I do in practice is manually add the friction back

I build with agentic workflows every day, and I no longer expect the base model to provide the right kind of resistance on its own.

So I add it procedurally.

In my own stack, one model orchestrates, another executes, and a separate reviewer checks every non-trivial PR without inheriting implementation context. I make the agent write plans before code. I force independent review from a different model with different context. I maintain project constitutions. I treat every clean-looking PR from an implementation agent as suspicious until it survives a second pass whose job is specifically to find architectural drift.

That works well enough to be useful. It does not work well enough to disappear.

The hardest reviews are not the obvious failures. The hardest reviews are the PRs that are correct by the ticket, clean by local standards, and still wrong for the direction of the system. Those are the ones that create alignment debt. Those are the ones a yes-man model will happily hand me all week.

So when people ask what still blocks fully autonomous software development, my answer is not "coding ability" in the narrow sense. The models are already good enough at producing code. The blocker is that they still do not reliably know when to resist me.

Until they do, friction has to be reintroduced by hand. And until that happens, the biggest risk in AI-assisted development is not that the model fails loudly. It is that it succeeds obediently.
